{{Infobox flag |Name = Liechtenstein |Article = |Image = Flag of Liechtenstein.svg |Use = 110000 |Symbol = |Proportion = 3:5 |Adoption = June 30, 1982 |Design = Horizontal bicolour of [[blue]] and [[red]]; [[charge (heraldry)|charged]] with a gold [[crown (headgear)|crown]] in the [[canton (heraldry)|canton]] |Type = National }}
The '''flag of [[Liechtenstein]]''' ({{lang-de|Flagge Liechtensteins}}) consists of two horizontal blue and red bands [[Charge (heraldry)|charged]] with a gold crown at the [[Glossary of vexillology#Description of standard flag parts and terms|canton]]. Adopted in 1921 after being officially enshrined into the [[Constitution of Liechtenstein|nation's constitution]], it has been the flag of the Principality of [[Liechtenstein]] since that year. The crown was added to the flag in 1937 after the country found out at the [[1936 Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics held the previous year]] that their flag was identical to the [[flag of Haiti]].
==History== [[File:Liechtenstein schaan flags 2009-08-15.jpg|thumb|120px|When flown vertically the crown on the flag is rotated so that it always faces upwards. (The flag on the left is that of Liechtenstein)]] Liechtenstein was formed in 1719 as a [[principality]] within the [[Holy Roman Empire]], and gained complete independence in 1866.<ref>{{cite news|title=Liechtenstein profile|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-17536865|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=|accessdate=June 26, 2014}}</ref> Within this period, the colours blue and red were selected to feature on the flag, instead of the gold and red on [[Coat of arms of Liechtenstein|the coat of arms]] that would have customarily been employed instead. These new livery colours were first utilized by [[Joseph Wenzel I, Prince of Liechtenstein|Prince Joseph Wenzel I]] in 1764.<ref name=EB>{{cite encyclopedia|first=Whitney|last=Smith|encyclopedia=Encyclopædia Britannica|title=Flag of Liechtenstein|url=http://global.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/1355360/flag-of-Liechtenstein|date=July 17, 2013|accessdate=June 26, 2014|publisher=Encyclopædia Britannica, Inc.}} '''{{subscription required}}</ref>
A [[Constitution of Liechtenstein|new constitution]] for the Principality was formulated and proclaimed in October 1921.<ref name=EB/><ref>{{cite web|title=History of Liechtenstein|url=http://www.lonelyplanet.com/liechtenstein/history|date=|accessdate=June 26, 2014|publisher=Lonely Planet}}</ref> It made the blue and red banner the national flag by granting it "official status".<ref name=EB/> Fifteen years later, during the [[1936 Summer Olympics]], the country came to the realization that its flag was identical to the [[flag of Haiti]], even though Haiti [[1936 Summer Olympics#Participating nations|did not participate in the Olympics]] that year. Because of this finding, the government added the prince's crown to the canton.<ref name=EB/><ref name=CIA>{{cite web|title=Liechtenstein|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ls.html|date=|accessdate=June 26, 2014|work=The World Factbook|publisher=CIA}}</ref><ref name=reuters>{{cite news|title=Flag bearing: a potted history|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/07/24/us-oly-flags-adv-idUSBRE86N0R420120724|date=July 24, 2012|accessdate=June 26, 2014|first=Venetia|last=Rainey|agency=Reuters}}</ref> This change served two purposes – to signify Liechtenstein's position as a principality, and to distinguish its flag from Haiti's.<ref name=CIA/><ref name=complete>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ZauSgqSl6ekC&pg=PA148&dq=flag+of+liechtenstein#v=onepage&q=flag%20of%20liechtenstein&f=false|title=Complete Flags of the World|publisher=Dorling Kindersley Ltd.|date=November 3, 2008|last=Kindersley|first=Dorling|pages=148|accessdate=June 26, 2014|isbn=9781405338615}}</ref> This modified design was adopted on June 24, 1937.<ref name=complete/>
==Design== ===Construction=== [[File:Flag of Liechtenstein (construction).svg|thumb|500px|center|Construction sheet for the Liechtenstein flag.]]
===Symbolism=== The colors and symbols of the flag carry cultural, political, and regional meanings. The blue represents the [[sky]], while red alludes to the "evening fires" that are lit inside houses throughout the country.<ref name=EB/> The crown – whose colour is disputed – epitomizes the "unity of the people and their [[Monarchy of Liechtenstein|prince]]."<ref name=EB/> While ''[[The World Factbook]]'' and [[Reuters]] describe it as gold in colour,<ref name=CIA/><ref name=reuters/> other sources – such as [[Whitney Smith]] in the ''[[Encyclopædia Britannica]]'' – describe it as yellow.<ref name=EB/><ref name=complete/>
==Legal issues== In February 2004, the [[Financial intelligence|Financial Intelligence Unit]] (FIU) of Liechtenstein called for the capture of a [[Dassault Falcon 50|Falcon 50]] private jet that was owned by the [[Ba'athist Iraq|former regime]] of [[Saddam Hussein]] and kept in [[Amman|Amman, Jordan]]. They sought this action because the plane flew the flag of Liechtenstein and had a registration number from [[Switzerland]], which keeps the civil aviation records of the Principality. This was carried out shortly afterwards in order to comply with [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1483]].<ref>{{cite news|title={{sic|Lei|chtenstein|nolink=y}} orders seizure of Saddam jet in Amman|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:WAFP&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=100F77D92233EF11&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=105B9A93AF33E3E3|date=February 26, 2004|accessdate=June 26, 2014|agency=Agence France-Presse}} '''{{subscription required}}</ref> After being transported to [[Basel]] and revamped entirely, the Liechtensteiner government returned the plane to the new [[Federal government of Iraq|government of Iraq]] on December 5, 2005. This marked the first Iraqi aircraft seized under UN sanctions to be given back to the country.<ref>{{cite news|title=Saddam plane handed over|url=http://www.compasscayman.com/caycompass/2005/12/06/Saddam-plane-handed-over/|date=December 5, 2005|accessdate=June 26, 2014|newspaper=Cayman Compass|agency=Associated Press|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303213910/http://www.compasscayman.com/caycompass/2005/12/06/Saddam-plane-handed-over/|archivedate=March 3, 2016|df=}}</ref>
