{{expert-subject|Iranian popular culture|date=July 2011}}
}}

'''Mareke Giri''' is a traditional public show in [[Iran]]. The ''Mareke Gir'' is a person who entertains people with his "special powers", such as breaking chains with his arms, breaking stones with his hands and [[Snake handling|handling snakes]]. Mareke Giri is a free show; people will give the Mareke Gir some money to encourage him.

[[Category:Iranian culture]]


{{iran-stub}}

{{Use Australian English|date=October 2018}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}
The '''Norweilemil''' were an [[indigenous Australian]] people of the [[Northern Territory]].
==Country==
The were a small tribe with, in [[Norman Tindale|Tindale]]'s estimation, some 400 sq. miles of territory  on the southeastern flank of the [[Van Diemen Gulf]], and west of the [[Alligator Rivers|West Alligator River]]. They were also attested around Stuart Point. {{sfn|Tindale|1974|p=234}}
==Practices==
[[Baldwin Spencer]] classifies them with  many other contiguous tribes in that area:-
<blockquote>To the same group of tribes belong, apparently, the [[Ngormbur|Koarnbut]], Quiradara, Norweilemil, [[Puneitja|Punuurlu]], [[Djowei|Kumertuo]], [[Gunwinggu|Geimbio]], Malanji, and, possibly, the [[Larrakia|Larakia]]. These, together with the [[Iwaidja|Iwaldji]], [[Gaagudju|Kakadu]], and the [[Melville Island (Australia)|Melville]] and [[Bathurst Island (Northern Territory)|Bathurst Islander]]s, form a group of tribes sharply marked off, not only by the absence of class organisation, but by the fact that their initiation ceremonies are distinguished by the absence of both circumcision and [[subincision]].{{sfn|Spencer|1914|p=52, cf.p=89}}</blockquote>

He also adds that, like the others, they do not appear to have used [[bullroarer]]s.{{sfn|Spencer|1914|p=211}}

==Alternative names==
* ''Lemil.'' (?){{sfn|Spencer|1914|p=90}}
* ''Noalanji.''{{efn|Spencer distinguishes the Noalanji from the Norweilemil, a distinction apparently ignored by Tindale.{{sfn|Spencer|1914|p=89}}}}

