{{Infobox artifact | name = Spillings Hoard | image = [[File:Spillings Silver Hoard 2 closeup.jpg|250px]] | image2 = [[File:Location of Spillings, Gotland.jpg|180px]] | image_caption = A part of cache No 2 of the Spillings Hoard in the Gotland Museum | material = [[Silver]], [[Bronze]] | size = {{convert|40|kg|lb|abbr=on}} plus {{convert|27|kg|lb|abbr=on}} plus {{convert|20|kg|lb|abbr=on}} | writing = | created = 9th century | discovered_place = Spillings, Othem, [[Gotland]], Sweden | discovered_coords = {{coord|57.721608|18.780352|display=title}} | discovered_date = 16{{nbsp}}July 1999 | discovered_by = Jonas Ström and Kenneth Jonsson | location = [[Gotland Museum]] | period = [[Viking Age]] (late [[Iron Age]]) | id = [http://mis.historiska.se/mis/sok/fyndlokal.asp?lokalid=52803 52803] }}
The '''Spillings Hoard''' ({{lang-sv|Spillingsskatten}}) is the world's largest [[Viking Age|Viking]] silver treasure, found on Friday 16{{nbsp}}July 1999 in a field at the Spilling farm northwest of [[Slite]], on northern [[Gotland]], Sweden. The silver hoard consisted of two parts with a total weight of {{convert|67|kg|lb|abbr=on}} before [[Conservation (cultural heritage)|conservation]] and consisted of, among other things, 14,295 coins most of which were [[Islam]]ic from other countries. A third deposition containing over {{convert|20|kg|lb|abbr=on}} of [[bronze]] scrap-metal was also found. The three caches had been hidden under the floorboards of a Viking outhouse sometime during the 9th century.
== Discovery == On Friday 16{{nbsp}}July 1999, a team of reporters from the Swedish television [[TV4 (Sweden)|TV4]] were in the [[socken]] of Othem on Gotland to film a cultural feature from [[Almedalen Week]]. They chose to do a segment on the problem with [[Looting#Archaeological removals|looting]] of archaeological sites with archaeologist Jonas Ström acting as their guide along with Kenneth Jonsson, a professor of [[numismatics]], who happened to be on the island at that time.{{sfn|Pettersson|2009|p=14}} Spillings farm was selected for the filming since about 150 silver coins and bronze objects had been found there earlier by the landowner Björn Engström.<ref name=Moscow>{{cite web|last1=Lynn|first1=Jonathan|title=Biggest Viking Hoard Unveiled|url=http://www.themoscowtimes.com/news/article/biggest-viking-hoard-unveiled/245672.html|website=www.themoscowtimes.com|publisher=[[The Moscow Times]]|date=26 June 2002|accessdate=19 April 2015}}</ref>
With filming complete, Ström and Jonsson decided to continue their survey of the field. Twenty minutes after the TV-crew had left, they heard a strong signal from their [[metal detector]], which led them to the smaller of the two silver caches. A couple of hours later and only {{convert|3|m|ft|}} from the first find, they received another signal from the detector:<ref name=silverharvest />
{{quote|"The display blinked 'overload' and then it turned itself off."|Jonas Ström<ref name=silverharvest>{{cite web|last1=Reistad|first1=Helena|title=Silverskörd. Vi har tre månader på oss att se världens största vikingatida silverskatt – sedan åker den tillbaka till Gotland|trans-title=Silver harvest. We have three months to see it – after that it goes back to Gotland|url=http://www.dn.se/arkiv/stockholm/silverskord-vi-har-tre-manader-pa-oss-att-se-varldens|website=www.dn.se|publisher=[[Dagens Nyheter]]|date=14 June 2002|language=Swedish|accessdate=18 April 2015}}</ref>}}
The site was hurriedly cordoned off, back-up crew from the museum was sent for, permission for an archaeological excavation was immediately sought at the [[Gotland Municipality|County Administrative Board]] and guards were posted. However, instead of keeping the find a secret, the [[Gotland Museum]] decided to go public with the find immediately. During the first weekend, over 2,000 people visited the excavation site.{{sfn|Pettersson|2009|p=16}}
Some days later, the metal detector indicated a third metal cache approximately {{convert|1.5|m|ft|}} from the first find. The archaeologists concentrated on uncovering the two first finds before starting with the third. Due to the size of the hoards and the fragility of the objects, the bottom layers of the depositions were encapsulated in plaster. Only when they tried to lift the finds out of the soil did the archaeologists realize how heavy the hoards were. The smaller weighed {{convert|27|kg|lb|abbr=on}} and the larger one {{convert|40|kg|lb|abbr=on}}. An attempt to X-ray the finds at the local hospital failed because they contained so much silver that the X-ray plates remained blank.{{sfn|Pettersson|2009|pp=16–18}}
The larger find was intact but the smaller had been damaged by a plough. A previous landowner who visited the excavation commented that he had found metal wires around the find-spot several years earlier, but thinking that they were only steel wire, he had thrown them away. It was therefore concluded that the treasure had originally been even larger.{{sfn|Pettersson|2009|p=18}}
With the two first caches taken care of, the third deposition was excavated almost a year after the first discovery. It contained over {{convert|20|kg|lb|abbr=on}} of bronze scrap-metal, most of which had been partially melted into a 'cake'. This find was deemed even more valuable since very few finds contain such large amounts of bronze intended for smelting.{{sfn|Pettersson|2009|p=18}}
== Further excavations == [[File:Location of depositories in stone foundation, Spillings.jpg|thumb|Location of depositories in the stone foundation at Spillings]] Additional excavations were conducted in the summer of 2000 and in 2003-06. Remnants of wood, iron rivets and mounts as well as a lock mechanism were found, leading to the conclusion that the caches had been stored in chests.{{sfn|Pettersson|2009|pp=18–20}}
An extended survey and excavation revealed the foundations of a building and indicated that the hoards had been placed under the floorboards of what would probably have been a warehouse, shed or storage rather than a dwelling since it had no hearth. Carbon dating showed that the building had been in use between 540 and 1040.{{sfn|Pettersson|2009|p=20}} The foundations and the remaining [[posthole]]s indicated a regular Viking Age structure, about {{convert|10|by|15|m|ft|abbr=on}} with a slanting [[Cladium mariscus|sedge]]-covered roof, much like other similar finds on Gotland. It had been built on an older Iron Age foundation.{{sfn|Pettersson|2009|p=47}}
== Find == The silver deposits were roughly square-shaped with rounded corners, about {{convert|40|to|45|x|50|cm|in|abbr=on}}, suggesting that they had been in sacks of cloth, leather or pelt, inside boxes or chests of wood.{{sfn|Pettersson|2009|p=16}} In the bronze deposit were found substantial pieces of wood and iron, such as fittings, ironwork, nails and a lock-device, showing that the bronze had been kept in a sturdy chest. A carbon dating of the chest dated it to approximately 675, making it older than the objects stored inside it.{{sfn|Pettersson|2009|p=32}}
Although silver hoards and treasures are not unusual on Gotland, this was an exceptionally large find. One explanation may be found in the location near some of the island's best and most significant harbours during the Viking Age. The silver in the caches would have been enough to pay the tax to the Swedish king for all of Gotland for five years.{{sfn|Pettersson|2009|pp=20–24}}
The following surveys and excavations of the fields surrounding the find-site showed that the site had been inhabited continuously over 1,000 years up until the 19th century. Over 700 more objects were retrieved, such as objects of bronze and copper, fired clay, [[Viking art#Metal|clothes pins]], a piece of glass, tile pieces, chains, needles, glass beads, slag, iron nails, polished [[Gemstone|semi-precious stones]] and brick.{{sfn|Pettersson|2009|pp=34–36}}
The Spillings Hoard is the world's largest Viking silver treasure.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lansmuseetgotland.se/servlet/GetDoc?meta_id=1327 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100509231733/http://www.lansmuseetgotland.se/servlet/GetDoc?meta_id=1327 |archive-date=9 May 2010|title=Skatten från Spillings i Othem socken-världens största vikingatida silverskatt|trans-title=The Hoard from Spillings in Othem socken is the wold's largest Viking silver treasure |accessdate=18 April 2015 |website=www.lansmuseetgotland.se |publisher=[[Gotland Museum]]|language=Swedish}}</ref> A finder's fee of [[Swedish krona|SEK]] 2,091,672 (approx. US$242,400) was paid to the landowner for the treasure, although the real value of it is much higher. It was the largest amount of money ever paid for a find in Sweden, according to director of the [[Swedish National Heritage Board]] Sven Göthe.<ref>{{cite web|last1=TT|title=Hittade vikingaskatt – får 2,1 miljoner i hittelön|trans-title=Found Viking treasure – gets 2.1 million in finder's fee|url=http://www.expressen.se/nyheter/hittade-vikingaskatt---far-21-miljoner-i-hittelon/|website=www.expressen.se|publisher=[[Expressen]]|date=21 December 2002|language=Swedish|accessdate=19 April 2015}}</ref> The hoard was dated to have been hidden some time after 870–71.{{sfn|Pettersson|2009|p=16}} The treasure is on permanent display in the Gotland Museum.<ref>{{cite web|title=Skattkammaren|trans-title=The Treasury|url=http://www.gotlandsmuseum.se/skattkammaren/|website=www.gotlandsmuseum.se|publisher=Gotland Museum|accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref>
{{As of|2015}}, more than {{convert|1000|kg|lb}} of silver from over 700 caches deposited between the 9th and 12th centuries have been found on Gotland. This includes 168,000 silver coins from the [[Arab world]], [[North Africa]] and [[Central Asia]].<ref name=gefle>{{cite web|last1=Thomsson|first1=Lena|title=Gotland & Spillingsskatten – obegripligt negligerade|trans-title=Gotland & The Spilling Hoard – inexplicably neglected|url=http://www.gd.se/kultur/bocker/gotland-spillingsskatten-obegripligt-negligerade|website=www.gd.se|date=9 February 2010|publisher=Gefle Dagblad|language=Swedish|accessdate=19 April 2015}}</ref>
== Silver depositions == The caches contained silver objects ranging from coins, bars, thread and [[hacksilver]] to be used as raw material, to jewelry such as fingerings, bangles and pendants. Much of the material had been bundled up to correspond with the mark-weight system of the Viking Age, in which {{convert|200|g|lb}} made one [[Mark (unit)|mark]].{{sfn|Pettersson|2009|p=24}}
Almost 60% of the find consisted of 486 [[bangle]]s or parts thereof, making it the largest ever find of such silver jewellery {{as of|2015|lc=y}}. Most of the bracelets weighed around 100 grams under the mark-weight system and were of traditional Gotlandic design, a number of them have very detailed ornamentation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Unikt mynt hittat i Spillingsskatten |trans-title=Unique coin found in the Spillings Hoard|url=http://www.hallekis.com/arkiv1/xx020629e.htm |work=Hällekis Kuriren |date=29 June 2002 |accessdate=2009-02-24}}</ref> There were also bangles of British and Western Scandinavian design as well as plain, undecorated fingerings of Finnish and British design, known as ''ring money''.{{sfn|Pettersson|2009|p=26}}
[[File:Khazar coin Spillings Hoard.jpg|thumb|150px|Khazar coin, {{circa}} 800]] Of the 14,295 coins found, 14,200 were Islamic [[dirham]]s,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Fadlan|first1=Ibn|author-link= Ahmad ibn Fadlan |title=Ibn Fadlan and the Land of Darkness: Arab Travellers in the Far North|date=2012|publisher=Penguin|location=London|isbn=0-14-197504-0|pages=Appendix 1|url=https://books.google.com/?id=UPCworiqUqcC&dq=spillings+hoard|accessdate=19 April 2015}}</ref> four were Nordic (from [[Hedeby]]), one was [[Byzantium|Byzantine]] and 23 were from [[Iran|Persia]]. The earliest, a Persian coin, dates from 539 and the latest from 870.<ref name="Moscow" /> Many of the coins (as well as the bangles) had marks that may have been made when the purity of the silver was [[Touchstone (assaying tool)|tested]].<ref name=silk>{{cite web|last1=Waugh|first1=Daniel C.|title=The Silk Road|url=http://www.silkroadfoundation.org/newsletter/vol9/srjournal_v9.pdf|website=www.silkroadfoundation.org|publisher=The Silkroad Foundation|page=168|accessdate=19 April 2015}}</ref> There were several imitations and fakes among the coins. The illegal copies were made from good silver, but made in other places than where the originals were minted. All in all, 69 different minting locations from 15 present-day countries were identified in the hoard.{{sfn|Pettersson|2009|pp=28–31}}
During the conservation work of the larger hoard (No 2) it became evident that the larger objects had been placed at the bottom of the cache and the smaller ones, ending with the cut coins, had been strewn on top.{{sfn|Pettersson|2009|p=22}}
=== Moses coin === One of the most noted coins in the hoard, dated to {{circa}} 800,{{sfn|Pettersson|2009|p=29}} is from the [[Khazars|Khazar Kingdom]] and designated the "Moses Coin". According to written sources the Khazars are believed to be Hebrews, but few objects have been found to support this claim.<ref name="Moscow" /> The coin is inscribed with "Moses is the messenger of God" instead of the usual Muslim text "Muhammad is the messenger of God".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Brook|first1=Kevin Alan|title=The Jews of Khazaria|date=2006|publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield]]|location=Lanham, Maryland|isbn=1-4422-0302-1|page=80|edition=2|url=https://books.google.com/?id=hEuIveNl9kcC&dq=spillings+hoard|accessdate=19 April 2015}}</ref>
== Bronze deposition == [[File:The s k cake Spillings Bronze Hoard.jpg|thumb|The "cake" from the bronze cache]] Excavated in the same manner as the silver hoards, the bronze cache was encapsulated on site and transported to the Gotland Museum for further examination. The objects were removed layer after layer from top to bottom until the large melted 'cake', about {{convert|40|cm|in|abbr=on}} in diameter was uncovered. Most of the bronze objects were broken, fragmented or partially melted, suggesting that they were kept in the heartwood chest to be used as raw material for new artifacts. Individual finds consisted of parts of, and some complete, necklaces, bangles, fingerings, pins for clothes and mounts for drinking horns. The bronze objects span a period of 200–300 years and are mostly of [[Baltic states|Baltic]] origin or possibly Russian with only a few of them Scandinavian. Even though several scholars have been involved in identifying the deposition, no consensus have been reached regarding why the hoard was collected or the dating of it. Two theories are that it was either the stock of a foundryman living on Gotland, or booty from a Viking raid that was hidden under the floor of the outhouse.{{sfn|Pettersson|2009|pp=31–34}} {{clear}}
== Gallery == <gallery mode="packed" height="120px"> File:Silver bars Spillings Hoard 2.jpg|Silver melted into bars from hoard No 2. File:Silver tangle Spillings Hoard 1.jpg|Silver tangle from hoard No 1. This one weighs about 2000 gram, about 10 silver marks in the old Gotlandic system where silver was used as currency. File:Coins Spilling Silver Hoard 2 closeup.jpg|Closeup of silver coins from hoard No 2. File:Iron fittings from a chest Spilling Hoard.jpg|Iron fittings from the chest in the bronze cache. </gallery>
