{{infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = The Last Sherlock Holmes Story | title_orig = | translator = | image = File:TheLastSherlockHolmesStory.jpg | caption = First UK edition | author = [[Michael Dibdin]] | cover_artist = | country = | language = [[Gujarati language|English]] | series = | genre = [[Mystery novels]] | publisher = [[Jonathan Cape]] (UK) | release_date = 1978 | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover|Hardback]] & [[Paperback]]) | pages = 192 | isbn = 0-224-01578-8 | dewey= | congress= | oclc= | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''The Last Sherlock Holmes Story''''' is a [[Sherlock Holmes pastiches|Sherlock Holmes pastiche]] [[novel]] by [[Michael Dibdin]].
The novel is an account of Holmes' attempt to solve the [[Jack the Ripper]] murders. Holmes suspects the Ripper to be his nemesis, [[Professor Moriarty|James Moriarty]].<ref>[http://capturescrime.blogspot.com/2009/12/last-sherlock-holmes-story-by-michael.html The Last Sherlock Holmes Story by Michael Dibdin]</ref> There is a twist ending, revealing that Holmes himself had invented the character of Moriarty due to insanity, and was himself committing the crimes, a twist which some reviewers have found to be clever<ref>[http://www.trashfiction.co.uk/sherlock_last.html ''The Last Sherlock Holmes Story''] review at Trashfiction.co.uk</ref> while others found disappointing. There is also an ambiguity to the revelation as, despairing, Holmes tries to explain to his companion [[Dr. Watson|Dr. John H. Watson]] that Moriarty has fooled Watson and framed Holmes.<ref>[http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/76207.The_Last_Sherlock_Holmes_Story ''The Last Sherlock Holmes Story''] review at goodreads</ref><ref>[http://www.epinions.com/review/The_Last_Sherlock_Holmes_Story_by_Michael_Dibdin/content_38862687876 ''The Last Sherlock Holmes Story''] review at epinions</ref>
